By the end of the course, students are expected to have achieved the following through intensive reading, intensive writing, and analysis of the structure of language and texts using linguistics concepts:
a. An understanding of the complexities involved in the process of reading and writing, and the elements that contribute to effective reading and effective writing;
b. The ability to articulate ideas in clear and precise language, and organize them coherently and logically in a text of extended length;
c. The ability to write a thesis statement to express the controlling idea of a composition, and to write topic sentences of paragraphs, as a major strategy for academic writing;
d. An understanding of how one can use paragraphing to help present one's ideas, and an awareness of larger textual patterns that enhance the richness of expressions and effectiveness in argumentation;
e. An enhanced knowledge of some of the typical errors of advanced Chinese learners of English, based on in-depth lexical and grammatical analysis;
f. An elementary understanding of levels of formality and stylistic registers in writing;
g. A basic command of the standard tools that are useful for writing: dictionaries, thesauruses, reference grammars, usage manuals, style sheets, and programs for preparing bibliographies.

By the end of the course, students are expected to have achieved the following, through intensive reading of linguistics articles in both English and Chinese, detailed discussion of the units and categories of language, and reflections on various phenomena related to phonology, syntax, and semantics:
a) A clear understanding of the basic units and categories of language; phoneme and distinctive feature; morpheme and word; syntactic categories and phrasal structure; an ability to define these units and categories, and justify why particular words and phrases belong to them;
b) The ability to describe the structure of argumentation of a linguistics article, and respond to the ideas contained in it;
c) An understanding of some standard arguments used in the analysis of sound patterns, sentence structure and meaning relations;
d) An interest to observe the languages encountered in daily life, and some skills in tapping into one's own native language competence;
e) A sensitivity to the possibility of alternative analyses for the same linguistic phenomena, and an elementary grasp of the methodological reasons for favoring one analysis over another, with reference to criteria such as economy, internal consistency, pattern congruity, linguistically significant generalizations and learnability;
f) Some familiarity with the standard Chinese linguistics terms used for basic concepts in general linguistics; some familiarity with the use of English as a meta-language to discuss data from other languages, in particular Chinese;
g) An enhanced ability to write clear, well-organized and coherent expository papers on language, making use of techniques such as formulating thesis statements, paragraphing and self-editing;
h) An enhanced knowledge of some of the typical errors of advanced Chinese learners of English, based on in-depth lexical and grammatical analysis;
i) A basic command of the use of reference grammars for descriptive facts about a language.

Students are expected to achieve the following learning outcomes:

* Discuss the social factors that influence language use;
* Identify the key issues in sociolinguistics and discuss these issues using the appropriate terminology;
* Identify common sociolinguistic phenomena in daily communication settings;
* Conduct basic analysis of sociolinguistic phenomena using the concepts learned in the course.

This course continues to further the goals of syntax I and aims
• to familiarize students with the goals, core assumptions and technical notions in the P&P modal of the generative grammar;
• to train students to be able to construct diagnostic tests to identify structural patterns, and become familiar with argumentation in syntax;
• to familiarize students with major constructions that have important bearings on Universal Grammar and parametric differences;
• To help students further develop skills in logical analysis and critical thinking.

- students will have a good understanding of the mental processes involved in language production and perception, and can integrate knowledge acquired through other courses in linguistics;
- students will be introduced to the major models of language perception and processing, and be aware of the complexity involved in language communication;
- students will analyse simple psycholinguistic data and develop critical thinking skills;
- students will develop the ability to discuss and work in groups;
- student will learn how to do small-scale research and develop oral presentation skills.

- to introduce students to a particular area(s) of language and mind;
- to familiarize students with research methods used in psycholinguistic and neurolinguistics research;
- to be able to comprehend empirical research on language/mind and related areas;
- to conduct simple experimental research into language.

Special Topics in Linguistics can be any course on language structure and language use. The topics are different in each offering. With the exposure in various topics which are not covered in the regular linguistic programme, students' knowledge and understanding in different areas of linguistics will be broadened and enhanced.

- to introduce students to a particular area(s) of Linguistics;
- to familiarize students with the literature of that particular area of Linguistics;
- to apply linguistics knowledge into the analysis of language-related phenomena.

- to introduce students to a particular area(s) of Applied Linguistics;
- to familiarize students with the literature of Applied Linguistics;
- to apply linguistics knowledge into the analysis of language-related phenomena in Applied Linguistics.

By the end of the term, students should be able to:
1. Classify speech sounds according to articulatory criteria;
2. Use phonetic transcription to learn the pronunciation of new words;
3. Recognize and analyze the phonological structure of the word;
4. Be able to apply the phonological concepts into data analysis

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

1. Describe the general differences between first-language and second-language acquisition;
2. Explain and discuss the various factors – linguistic, psychological, social – which influence the learner’s acquisition of a second language;
3. Compare and discuss selected theories of second-language acquisition (SLA), and their implications for language teaching and learning;
4. Reflect critically on their personal second-language learning experience, and discuss and evaluate it in the light of current SLA theory and practice.

Upon successfully completing the subject, students should be able to:
1. To enhance students’ understanding of how meaning is made by means by grammar;
2. To foster students’ understanding of the place of grammar within a broader framework of communication;
3. To apply the concepts of syntactic analysis to describe the structure, meaning and use of English grammar;
4. To generalize from findings to establish rules;
5. To understand and use English effectively and accurately.

The course aims to achieve the following goals:
1. to familiarize students with basic goals and assumptions in the study of Chinese syntax and semantics;
2. to train students to identify meaning components and structural patterns and make sensible generalizations;
3. to train students in the rudiments of linguistic analysis and argumentation in syntax and semantics and apply them to Chinese;
4. to familiarize students with major meaning and structural properties in Chinese and extend them to their native language(s) to bring into light the relevance of linguistic theories

1. to acquire understandings of concepts, current issues and research methods in the core areas of applied linguistics;
2. to develop knowledge of theory and abilities to apply theory to professional and practical tasks in targeted areas of applied linguistics;
3. to lay a solid foundation for further studies in the field.

- students will have a good understanding of the mental processes involved in language production and perception, and can integrate knowledge acquired through other courses in linguistics;
- students will be introduced to the major models of language perception and processing, and be aware of the complexity involved in language communication;
- students will analyse simple psycholinguistic data and develop critical thinking skills;
- students will develop the ability to discuss and work in groups;
- student will learn how to do research and develop oral presentation skills.

Students are expected to achieve the following through a close reading of some of the classic writings in language acquisition, lectures, in-class discussions, writing assignments and the term project:
- -a basic understanding of the biological foundations of language, the situation of the language learner, and the relationship between the input to language acquisition and the ultimate linguistic knowledge attained;
- -a critical understanding of the fundamental assumptions underlying the nativist and the usage-based approaches to language acquisition, and the logic of argumentation in support of these approaches;
- -a basic knowledge of the modularity thesis on the architecture of mind, cognitive pre-requisites for the development of language, putative syntactic and semantic universals, and the ways in which language structure may facilitate the development of thought;
- -a basic grasp of how longitudinal and cross-sectional acquisition data are used to address issues in linguistics and language acquisition, as well as an ability to analyze acquisition data (in English, Mandarin or Cantonese) for structural patterns.
